Hello!

I noticed while browsing the docs that the documentation for the `_.reduce` function has the following section:

> Many lodash methods are guarded to work as iteratees for methods like _.reduce, _.reduceRight, and _.transform.
>
> The guarded methods are:
> assign, defaults, defaultsDeep, includes, merge, orderBy, and sortBy

I was a little intrigued by the inclusion of the `_.includes` function in that list, so I tried to use it with `_.reduce` in a bunch of different ways, including partially applying some part of the function and the likes, to see if it would work somehow through some kind of special treatment inside the function. But, as I was expecting, no luck.

So after searching a bit on the internet to see if I was missing something, I found at least one person as confused as I on StackOverflow.

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62295930/lodash-reduce-with-includes-or-orderby-iteratee-use-cases

Sadly the question had no answers, so I ended up digging the source code history a bit to see if I could make sense of this in my head, and I ended up finding that the change in the documentation (along with the guard in the `_.includes` function) was included in this commit: https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/eee714f52

With it there was also a test

```diff
diff --git a/test/test.js b/test/test.js
index 26a1b12963..a66c4e1c6b 100644
--- a/test/test.js
+++ b/test/test.js
@@ -6211,6 +6211,13 @@
       strictEqual(_.includes([-0], 0), true);
     });
 
+    test('should work as an iteratee for methods like `_.reduce`', 1, function() {
+      var array1 = [1, 2, 3],
+          array2 = [2, 3, 1];
+
+      ok(_.every(array1, _.partial(_.includes, array2)));
+    });
+
     test('should be aliased', 2, function() {
       strictEqual(_.contains, _.includes);
       strictEqual(_.include, _.includes);
```

but it seems the test actually uses the `_.every` function.

I also found out that the test description was actually changed when the separate `lodashStable` was added to the test suite in this commit https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/fdf6478bc.

```diff
diff --git a/test/test.js b/test/test.js
index 46dbb44735..50f8364a9a 100644
--- a/test/test.js
+++ b/test/test.js
@@ -6344,13 +6339,13 @@
       assert.strictEqual(_.includes([0], -0), true);
     });
 
-    QUnit.test('should work as an iteratee for methods like `_.reduce`', function(assert) {
+    QUnit.test('should work as an iteratee for methods like `_.every`', function(assert) {
       assert.expect(1);
 
       var array1 = [1, 2, 3],
           array2 = [2, 3, 1];
 
-      assert.ok(_.every(array1, _.partial(_.includes, array2)));
+      assert.ok(lodashStable.every(array1, lodashStable.partial(_.includes, array2)));
     });
   }(1, 2, 3, 4));
```

So I'm not quite sure if I would classify the current docs as plain wrong, since it does not tie **specifically** to the `_.reduce` function (though it _**is**_ located in the `_.reduce` section), but I do think it needs at least some clarification.

Something to make sure people won't think there's some classic lodashy way of elegantly mixing those two functions (`_.reduce` and `_.includes`).

(And if there actually is some elegant way that I missed to mix those two because of the guard on `_.includes`, then I think it would be cool if it could be added to the example block in the `_.reduce` section).

