Truncate is not a terribly advanced/complicated function, but *at minimum*, unless you want your string truncated at exactly 30 characters, it requires this:

    truncate(aReallyLongString, { length: 100 });

That's not terrible, but it's uncharacteristically verbose for Lodash.  Consider the signature of a very similar method, `pad`:

    pad('abc', 8);

Why not allow a non-object signature of `truncate(string, length, omission, separator)`? Looking at the source, it seems it'd be trivial to add another signature to `truncate`, as it would simply require one new `else if`  clause:

    function truncate(string, options) {
      // ..
       if (isObject(options)) {
         // set variables from options

       // NEW CODE
       } else if (isInteger(options)) {

Surely `truncate` isn't likely to take any new options anytime soon, and this would enable it to be used simply/elegantly, the same way as most Lodash functions:  

    pad('abc', 8);

    truncate(aReallyLongString, 100);

I'd be happy to submit a PR if this is desired.

P.S. And unless someone is currently passing integers to `truncate` now (in place of that object argument, despite said integer doing nothing) .... which I guess is *possible*, but I can't imagine is very common ... this would have zero negative impact on anyone.
